SIMPLE: evaporation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Evaporation
<hw>E*vap`o*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>evaporatio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>⟦eacute⟧vaporation</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The process by which any substance is converted from a
liquid state into, and carried off in, vapor; <as>as, the
<ex>evaporation</ex> of water, of ether, of camphor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The transformation of a portion of a fluid into
vapor, in order to obtain the fixed matter contained in it in a state of
greater consistence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>That which is evaporated; vapor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Steam Engine)</fld> <def>See
<er>Vaporization</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Evaporative</ent>⟦br⟧
